As of May 6, 2021, two days after this forecast, a viable consensus forecast I put together by selecting forecasters that I think do pretty well resulted in possible outcomes between the last two bins: 48% chance Between 17.5 million and 19.0 million, inclusive; 52% chance More than 19.0 million.

Cases have been declining since late March. It had not been clear to me whether this represented a temporary dip on a continued way up or a more substantial decline. It's now going on long enough that it seems to me that the current decline is likely not just "noise" on the way up. However, I still firmly believe that Brazil will see >19.0M cases by July 31 because the peak respiratory virus season is approximately from now through the end of July, there is no concerted national effort to stem transmission, and vaccination is proceeding slowly and primarily with a vaccine that has been found to be 50% effective at preventing cases in Brazil. It is as inconceivable to me that there will not be a winter peak in cases of a respiratory virus in Brazil as it was that the US would not see an increase in cases last fall and winter. Spreading in fall, winter and spring is what respiratory viruses do. Even if cases continue to decline a bit more, I am confident that they will be heading back up within the forecast period. There are 4.22M cases to go to reach 19.0M, and 89 days remaining in the forecast period; it will take an average of 47.4k cases/day to reach 19M, and Brazil is currently at a 7-day average of 58.6k cases/day.

Ok, I'm trying hard to force myself to strategize about the Brier score. I'm updating from a previous forecast of 100% for >19.0M, not because I currently think there's actually any chance it'll be under 19.0M, but because I recognize that I could be wrong and that the Brier score will penalize me much more harshly for a 100% forecast than for a lower forecast if I am wrong.

My approach was to take about 20 countries which have similar GDP, and for all 20 look at % development in total cases across last 3 months. All countries will be at different stages of second wave, third wave, etc. so hopefully a good range of outcomes. None have significant vaccinations programs. Of 20 countries, 19 had increased total cases by > 50% in last 3 months. I've therefore assessed Brazil >19m total cases (a 30% increase on current), to have a approx. 95% chance.
Not near herd immunity. Using Sinovac which has a lower effectiveness. Community transmission still active.

The question really is the impact of the two variants that have emerged in Brazil and the effectiveness of the vaccine to respond. Additionally, will the Brazilian government get serious about putting COVID restrictions in place (probably not) or will the citizens take a more proactive approach to protect themselves (possibly, but probably with limited impact). I am modifying my forecast slightly, based on the likelihood that while conditions in Brazil will remain pretty bad, the county has probably seen the worse and COVID cases will begin to decline. Increasing the probability of "Between 17.5 million and 19.0 million, inclusive" to 21% from 16%. Maintaining a 2% optimism that it will be below 17.5 million.

I wish I could be more confident that the decline will persist, and I was probably overconfident last time, but it's difficult to say why the numbers are declining currently so hard to forecast if whatever's driving it will persist. Could be young people realizing they're at risk given the variant, could be local responses in response to abysmal national leadership, could be people being scared of getting tested amid the outbreak or issues with testing not getting attention. Like in the previous prediction, I assumed a linear curve. This was due to data showing an approximately stable curve from late March. Knowing, due to @belikewater that the recent numbers were a likely Easter dip, I ignored them in favor of numbers closer to the 31st. Knowing that individual day results were deceptive, I used a 7- day average. 107*75349+ 13 677 564 (cases to date)=21 739 907. My previous result was based on a 60 day window. How embarrassing. That being said, immunizations will bring the result down. At some point, the Brazilian strain will run out of people to infect in the North. The question is: how soon will it be under control in the south? (probably not soon, I would imagine?) From these points, @belikewater makes some excellent points. Yes, we will quite likely see >20M cases by then. ~3M spare, assuming the vaccine makes a meaningful difference.

As of Mar 18 there are 11.7M confirmed cases, a 7 day average of 70k cases per day, and the average is increasing by ~500 cases per day. 4.5% of the population is vaccinated and 350k/day are being vaccinated currently (.16% per day). At current rate an addtional 21.6% of the population will be vaccinated by July 31 (Total 26.1%). P.1 Strain is well on its way to being the dominant strain in Brazil, is 1.4-2.2 times more contagious, 25-61% more capable of re-infection, and evidence points to the SinoVac Vaccine being ineffective against it (which accounts for ~70% of vaccinations). If the SinoVac vaccine is ineffective, and the other vaccines are ~95% effective, as of July 31 effectively 5% of the population (11 million) will be immune via vaccination. 12 million have been infected meaning ~23 million (~11%) are effectively immune. If trend continues ~17M additional cases could occur, assume less 12% due to vaccination putting the high end total at ~25M. If the vaccine is 100% effective the infection rate should also drop, so 40% less than high estimate, meaning 10M new infections for 21.7M total. There are currently no restrictions in place and even an extreme lockdown is unlikely to change the outlook in the next 2-4 weeks. Although infection has proven not linear it seems likely an ongoing rapid increase in infections will be followed by a later decrease but should even out over the given timeframe. The new health minister seems unlikely to impose a lockdown currently. More aggressive measures seem possible but unlikely in the near term (2-4 weeks) and better vaccine procurement is in process, so it seems most likely it will be over 19M cases.
